  "prompt": "The resultant of two forces has magnitude 20N. One of the forces has magnitude 20\u221a3N making an angle of 30\u00b0 with the resultant? What is the magnitude of the other force?",
  "response": "To find the magnitude of the other force, we can use the law of cosines in the triangle formed by the two forces and their resultant.\n\nLet:\n- \\( R \\) be the magnitude of the resultant force (20 N),\n- \\( F_1 \\) be the magnitude of the first force (20\u221a3 N),\n- \\( F_2 \\) be the magnitude of the second force (let's denote it as \\( F_2 \\)),\n- \\( \\theta \\) be the angle between \\( F_1 \\) and the resultant \\( R \\) (30\u00b0).\n\nUsing the law of cosines:\n\\[\nR^2 = F_1^2 + F_2^2 - 2 F_1 F_2 \\cos(\\theta)\n\\]\n\nSubstituting the known values:\n\\[\n20^2 = (20\\sqrt{3})^2 + F_2^2 - 2 (20\\sqrt{3}) F_2 \\cos(30\u00b0)\n\\]\n\nCalculating each term:\n- \\( R^2 = 400 \\)\n- \\( (20\\sqrt{3})^2 = 400 \\times 3 = 1200 \\)\n- \\( \\cos(30\u00b0) = \\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2} \\)\n\nSubstituting these back into the equation:\n\\[\n400 = 1200 + F_2^2 - 2 (20\\sqrt{3}) F_2 \\left(\\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2}\\right)\n\\]\n\\[\n400 = 1200 + F_2^2 - 20\\sqrt{3} F_2 \\sqrt{3}\n\\]\n\\[\n400 = 1200 + F_2^2 - 60 F_2\n\\]\n\nNow, rearranging the equation:\n\\[\nF_2^2 - 60 F_2 + 1200 - 400 = 0\n\\]\n\\[\nF_2^2 - 60 F_2 + 800 = 0\n\\]\n\nNext, we can solve this quadratic equation using the quadratic formula:\n\\[\nF_2 = \\frac{-b \\pm \\sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{2a}\n\\]\n\nWhere \\( a = 1 \\), \\( b = -60 \\), and \\( c = 800 \\):\n\\[\nF_2 = \\frac{-(-60) \\pm \\sqrt{(-60)^2 - 4 \\times 1 \\times 800}}{2 \\times 1}\n\\]\n\\[\nF_2 = \\frac{60 \\pm \\sqrt{3600 - 3200}}{2}\n\\]\n\\[\nF_2 = \\frac{60 \\pm \\sqrt{400}}{2}\n\\]\n\\[\nF_2 = \\frac{60 \\pm 20}{2}\n\\]\n\nCalculating the two potential solutions:\n1. \\( F_2 = \\frac{80}{2} = 40 \\)\n2. \\( F_2 = \\frac{40}{2} = 20 \\)\n\nThus, the magnitude of the other force \\( F_2 \\) can be either \\( 40 \\, \\text{N} \\) or \\( 20 \\, \\text{N} \\). Therefore, the possible magnitudes of the second force are:\n\n\\[\n\\boxed{40 \\, \\text{N}} \\quad \\text{or} \\quad \\boxed{20 \\, \\text{N}}\n\\]",
